Due to the increased positivity rate of COVID-19 in Jackson County, the following precautions will be taken at all of our home events, effective immediately:

1) Face coverings are REQUIRED at all indoor and outdoor activities.
2) Fans must leave every other row of bleachers empty to allow for social distancing. Bleachers will be marked.
3) Elementary-aged students (PK-5th grade) are required to sit with their families.
4) No throwing/kicking of balls or running around.
5) No food will be allowed in the gymnasiums ‚Äì only drinks. Food should be eaten in the cafeteria areas.

Thank you for your cooperation and understanding. These changes were made with the safety of our staff, students, fans, and visitors at the top of our priority list.

We ask that ALL comments, questions, and concerns regarding this decision are sent directly to the school by calling your student‚Äôs building office.

post_text:
In these difficult times, we are forced to look at things differently and make some very tough decisions.

Unfortunately, we must cancel this year‚Äôs Homecoming dance. The increased COVID-19 positivity rate in Jackson County prevents us from safely hosting the event without risking the health of our students and staff.

Student Senate is assembling this week to look at how other activities and events can be modified to ensure a safe and fun Homecoming Week. Additional plans and details will be released following their meeting.

Thank you for your patience and understanding, and please know that this decision was not made easily or lightly. We ask that ALL comments, questions, and concerns regarding this decision are sent directly to the high school by calling (563) 652-2451.

Reminder: Tomorrow is Remote Learning Friday!
A reminder to all Maquoketa Community School District families that every Friday is a remote/online learning day for your child(ren).

Your child‚Äôs teachers will post learning assignments/activities to their learning management system (Seesaw for PK-5th grade students and Canvas for 6th-12th grade students). Your child has accessed these programs throughout the week and should be familiar with how to locate their learning assignments. Please complete any assignments by Monday morning at 8:00 am for your child to be counted as ‚Äúpresent‚Äù for the Friday school day.

If your child is a remote learner they will also participate in Friday‚Äôs learning. Teachers will provide additional feedback to remote learners on Friday and begin to post assignments for the following week. All lesson information for Monday will be posted no later than Monday at 8:00 am.

Please reach out to your child‚Äôs teachers or principals if you have additional questions about Friday remote/online learning.

Thank You,
Maquoketa Community School District

post_text:
MIDDLE SCHOOL & HIGH SCHOOL STUDENTS AND FAMILIES:

Middle and High Schoolers are not using lockers at this time to support our mitigation efforts throughout the day.

Student's bags too heavy? Too much stuff to carry all day?

Here is how you can help!

Go through their bags together and help them minimize what they are bringing. They will not need ALL of their new supplies right now. If they bring a notebook, some loose paper, a few pencils, and they can leave excess supplies at home until they are needed.

Kleenex, GermX, and other donated supplies can be dropped off in the main office.

Musical Instruments should be stored in the band room during the day.

We understand this is out of the norm, but by mitigating hallway hangouts, this will help keep us all safer!

We can do this! Thank you for your support!

For the past several months 65 staff, students, and community members have been making plans in order for the students of the Maquoketa School District to return to their learning some way, somehow. The results of that hard work is the document that you are about to read.

Please understand that this document is meant to provide some general guidance and expectations while allowing for the flexibility in each building to address concerns and issues as they arise. Please also understand that the information contained within this document can, and will, change. As more details become available to us we will be able to better plan for certain scenarios.

Click the link below to read our Return to Learn Plan for the 2020-2021 school year:

https://sites.google.com/maquoketaschools.org/maquoketa-csd/return-to-learn-plans?authuser=0

post_text:
üéìATTENTION GRADUATES:üéì

As Sunday's commencement ceremony approaches, please keep the following reminders in mind:

-Each graduate will be allowed four guests. Graduates and guests must arrive at the same time, as guests will not be admitted if they are not in the presence of the graduate they are a guest of.
-Doors will open at 1:45 pm in an effort to reduce casual contact before the ceremony.
-Masks are strongly encouraged from the time you enter the building until you at least reach your seat.

We ask that any of our graduates or guests who are at high risk due to existing health conditions to please contact the school so we can discuss possible accommodations.

For a complete list of graduation reminders, please visit: https://www.maquoketaschools.org/graduation-letter/

It's time for 6th Grade!
Well it's that time of year, time to start thinking about moving on to the next grade. While we didn't get to end this year in the school building, we still wanted to give soon to be 6th grade students and parents some information to prepare for middle school next year. In this newsletter, we will give you some introduction videos of 6th grade teachers, survival tips, a virtual tour of Maquoketa Middle School, and a spot where you can submit any questions you may have about the transition to 6th grade.

Click the link below to read the full newsletter -->
From all the Briggs Teachers and Staff, we will miss you all very much!!

MHS Student Senate is sponsoring an activity to help everyone at the high school celebrate our school spirit at the end of the year.

We want to invite all students and staff to participate in the following dress up days:

Monday, May 18 - Decade Day

Tuesday, May 19 - Pajama Day

Wednesday, May 20 - Pattern Day

Thursday, May 21 - Character Day

Friday, May 22 - Spirit Day (in order to honor seniors, spring activity and sport participants, and all students)

Participants can email pictures of themselves to Mrs. Raker (araker@maquoketaschools.org) by Saturday, May 23. The pictures will be added to Google slides and the completed slides will be sent out to students and staff at MHS so you can see everyone's dress up day attire.

Thank you,

The Maquoketa administration continues to work with all of our partners to determine the best course of action when responding to the COVID-19 threat. post_text: Advanced math class at middle school used a hands on activity to discover and investigate slope. Theywent looked at the ways different athletic balls bounced. They investigated if their bounces stayed consistent between different drops in heights. They graphed them and will be extending their findings to see if they can create an equation to work with tennis, softballs, baseballs, golf balls, bouncy balls, and plastic balls.

post_text:
Congratulations to Mrs. Ackley for being nominated and selected for the Mississippi Bend AEA District Watch! This is award recognizes time, energy, talent, and all around dedication to the profession. It is given throughout all districts MBAEA supports, and is a great honor to receive.

Marisa was selected for being "a model for doing what it takes to support student learning and most recently has taken on the role of pioneering tier 3 intervention at her school to support infrastructure and intervention development. She is ALWAYS willing to learn and try new approaches to meet student needs and be a team player."

post_text: Cardinal students enjoyed a show this morning put on by the National Theater for Children called Showdown at Conservation Canyon. This show was sponsored by the Maquoketa WPPI Energy group and taught students about what energy is, how energy is wasted, and even how to conserve it. One of our students even got to play a deputy in the show! Be sure to ask your children about the show and work to conserve energy in your home!

post_text: Kindergarten, 1st, and 2nd grade students did a Christmas LEGO challenge during classroom guidance classes at Cardinal before winter break. They received a picture of a Christmas object and had to work together to build it. Other teams then guessed what it was! Students collaborated, practiced taking turns and sharing, and worked on managing their emotions during this fun STEM activity that aligns with ASCA (American School Counselor Association) standards!

post_text:
Hello Before/After School Program Families,

Our 3rd Quarter Before/After School program began yesterday and we are continuing to receive updates regarding student transportation needs. If you have changed your address or have changed from parent pick-up to needing bus transportation please call your child's building as soon as possible so we have accurate transportation information for your child.

Due to some of these changes, student drop-off times may vary from when they have been previously dropped off. The After School Program staff will do everything possible to contact families if busses are running behind schedule. If needing to contact the program after 4:00 pm, please call your child's attendance building and enter the prompt to contact the After School Coordinator on duty if you have questions or concerns regarding your child's arrival time. Thank you for your participation in this program and for your patience as we work to ensure that your child has fun and arrives home safely.

Before/After School Program Staff

English 105's Santa visiting Mrs. Owen's and Mrs. Klemme's kindergarten.

üéÑSanta, Will Lapke an English 105 student at the Maquoketa Center, hands Eli McNamee his letter from Santa's elf while Chloe Daniel, both from Mrs. Gavin's kindergarten at Cardinal, eagerly awaits her name to be called.

üéÑTallon LaMock, a student in Mrs. Snowden's kindergarten room, has assured Santa he has been good this year as he accepts his candy cane.

üéÑ After Santa handed out each child's letter the English 105 students read their letter to them. Allison Bohrman reads the letter from Ryno the Elf to Donnie Bessie.
